  "preamble": "You are given the complete specification for a desktop developer tool called NARUKAMI. Rebuild it faithfully as an npm-workspaces monorepo with three packages: `packages/backend` (Node + TypeScript + Fastify 5 + Prisma 6 over SQLite + node-pty + ws + Playwright), `packages/frontend` (React 18 + Vite 6 + Monaco + xterm), and `packages/desktop` (Electron 33 shell that embeds the backend and serves the built SPA, packaged with electron-builder + electron-updater). A single shared bearer token authenticates every HTTP and WebSocket call. Work through the sections in the order given, building and verifying one layer before the next: read the architecture, lay down the Prisma data model, then the backend REST API, its runner/broker/analyzer services and browser/render pipeline, then the WebSocket protocols, then the React frontend shell and views, then the Electron shell, and finally the build/run/deploy setup. Implement every endpoint, message shape, model, component, and script exactly as specified — do not invent features beyond what the sections describe. Ask before diverging from the documented contracts.",
  "intro": "## What NARUKAMI is\n\nNARUKAMI is a cross-platform developer cockpit for running software projects. You register a project by its path, let Claude Code analyze how it runs, and then launch each of its commands in its own live, in-app browser terminal. It ships two ways from a single codebase: as a native **Electron desktop app** (with an embedded backend and SQLite — no Docker, no external services) and as a **local web runner** you open in a browser. Around the core \"run a command and watch it live\" loop, NARUKAMI adds a Monaco code editor with a git gutter and file search, a token-usage dashboard, an end-of-day (EOD) summarizer, elevated (UAC/admin) shells brokered over a loopback socket, tear-off windows for terminals and previews, a multi-device browser preview that emulates Chromium and streams *real* Firefox/WebKit pixels via Playwright, and Claude-driven analysis that detects run commands, suggests commands, diagnoses failures, and writes EOD summaries headlessly.\n\n### Tech stack\n\n- **Monorepo:** npm workspaces with three packages — `packages/backend`, `packages/frontend`, `packages/desktop` — orchestrated in dev by `concurrently`.\n- **Backend:** Node + TypeScript, **Fastify 5** (`@fastify/cors`, `@fastify/static`), **Prisma 6** over **SQLite** (`@prisma/client`), **node-pty** for real PTYs, **ws** for WebSockets, **Playwright** for real browser rendering, `dotenv` for config. Built with `tsc`, run in dev via `tsx watch`, tested with `vitest`.\n- **Frontend:** **React 18** + **Vite 6**, **Monaco** (`@monaco-editor/react`, `monaco-editor`) for the editor, **xterm** (`@xterm/xterm` + `addon-fit`) for terminals, **three** for visuals, TypeScript, tested with `vitest`.\n- **Desktop:** **Electron 33** shell that boots the Fastify backend in-process and serves the built React SPA; packaged with **electron-builder** (Windows NSIS installer) and self-updating via **electron-updater**. node-pty, Prisma, and Playwright binaries are `asarUnpack`ed; the SQLite DB, MCP bridge, and broker agent ship as extra resources.\n- **Auth & IPC:** a shared **bearer token** (generated by `scripts/gen-token.mjs`) guards every HTTP and WebSocket call; a minimal Electron `contextBridge` preload exposes the backend URL/token and tear-off controls to the renderer.\n\n### How the three processes talk\n\nThe system is a three-tier pipeline where each layer owns one concern:\n\n1. **Electron shell (`packages/desktop`)** is the outermost process. Its main process spawns/embeds the Fastify backend, then loads the React SPA (built by Vite) into a `BrowserWindow`. A tiny preload `contextBridge` hands the renderer the backend's base URL and bearer token and exposes tear-off / re-dock window controls. In web-runner mode the shell is absent and the SPA is served directly by the backend's SPA middleware.\n2. **React frontend (`packages/frontend`)** runs in the renderer (or a browser). Its `App` shell holds global state, boots and restores UI from persisted `AppSetting` rows, switches views, and manages the terminal/browser tear-off dock. It talks to the backend two ways: a typed `api` HTTP client for REST (projects, files/git, runs, settings, EOD, telemetry, render, browser-accuracy), and **WebSockets** for anything live — `/ws/runs/:id` streams terminal I/O and `/ws/render` streams Playwright frames. Every request carries the bearer token.\n3. **Fastify backend (`packages/backend`)** is the single source of truth. It exposes the REST API, upgrades the two browser-facing WebSocket endpoints, persists everything to SQLite through Prisma, and runs the heavy machinery: a **runner/broker** that spawns and streams node-pty processes (plain runs, Claude sessions, and elevated admin shells via a UAC broker on a loopback TCP socket), an **analyzer** that drives `claude -p` headless, telemetry/git/config services, the browser-accuracy advisor, and the Playwright render pipeline. Live process output is streamed to clients and journaled to `RunLog` rows so terminals can be reconnected and replayed after a drop.\n\nIn short: **Electron wraps and boots → the React SPA drives the UI and holds session state → Fastify executes, streams, and persists.** REST handles request/response; WebSockets handle the live terminal and pixel streams; the bearer token authenticates all of it; SQLite/Prisma makes runs, logs, analyses, and UI state durable and restorable.\n\n### How to use this blueprint\n\nThis document is the complete specification for rebuilding NARUKAMI from scratch. Paste the preamble below to your own Claude, then feed it the sections in the order given. Each section is self-contained (architecture, an API surface, a service, a set of components, etc.) and anchored, so you can build and verify one layer before moving to the next. Build outward from the foundation: understand the shape of the system, lay down the data model, stand up the backend and its live protocols, then the frontend, then the desktop shell, and finally wire up build/run/deploy.\n\n### Recommended reading order\n\n1. **Architecture & Project Layout** (`architecture`) — the big picture and the monorepo shape.\n2. **Data Model** (`data-model`) — the Prisma schema + backend DTOs everything else builds on.\n3. **Backend HTTP API** (`backend-api`) — the REST surface, auth hook, CORS, and SPA middleware.\n4. **Backend Services — Process Running** (`backend-runner`) — the runner/broker/analyzer core loop.\n5. **Backend Services — Telemetry, Git, Config, Auth, DB** (`backend-services`) — the cross-cutting service layer.\n6. **Backend Services — Browser Accuracy & Real Rendering** (`backend-browser`) — the accuracy advisor and Playwright pipeline.\n7. **WebSocket Protocols** (`websockets`) — the live terminal, render, and broker socket message contracts.\n8. **Frontend — App Shell, State & API Client** (`frontend-shell`) — the React root, state/restore, and typed `api` client.\n9. **Frontend — Core Views** (`frontend-components-a`) — Panel, Sidebar, Editor, Dashboard, EOD, Live, Terminal.\n10. **Frontend — Browser View, Popouts, Chrome & Libraries** (`frontend-components-b`) — the browser preview, tear-off gestures, theming, and Electron bridge.\n11. **Desktop Shell** (`desktop-shell`) — the Electron main process, preload, and window management.\n12. **Build, Run & Deploy** (`build-run-deploy`) — install, dev, test, and package the self-updating installer.",
